#Text=Nehemiah Donnellan
#Text=For other uses , see Nehemiah Donnellan ( disambiguation ) .
#Text=Nehemiah Donnellan ( a. k. a. Fearganainm Ó Domhnalláin ) ( fl. c. 1560-1609 ) was Archbishop of Tuam .
#Text=Background
#Text=Donellan was born in the county of Galway , a son of Mael Sechlainn Ó Dónalláin , by his wife Sisly , daughter of William Ó Cellaigh of Calla .
#Text=He was a descendant of Domnallan mac Maelbrigdi .

#Text=He was entered as Nehemiah Daniel on 13 January 1579-80 at King 's College , Cambridge , and shortly afterwards matriculated in the same name . Subsequently , he migrated to Catharine Hall , where he took the degree of B.A. in 1581-2 .
#Text=Career

#Text=On his return to his native country he acted for some time as coadjutor to William Ó Maolalaidh , archbishop of Tuam , and afterwards , on the recommendation of Thomas , earl of Ormonde , he was appointed the successor of that prelate , by letters patent dated 17 August 1595 .
#Text=Two days later he received restitution of the temporalities .

#Text=In the writ of privy seal directing his appointment , it was alleged that he was very fit to communicate with the people in their mother tongue , and a very meet instrument to retain and instruct them in duty and religion ; and that he had also taken pains in translating and putting to the press the Communion Book and New Testament in the Irish language , which Her Majesty greatly approved of .

#Text=It is asserted by Teige Ó Dubhagáin ( see Dugan ) , who drew up a pedigree of the Donellan family , that he was never in holy orders , but probably the genealogist may have been led to make this startling assertion simply by an unwillingness to acknowledge the orders of the reformed church .

#Text=In addition to his see the archbishop held by dispensation the rectory of Kilmore in the county of Kilkenny , and the vicarages of Castle-doagh in the diocese of Ossory , and of Donard in the diocese of Dublin .
#Text=He voluntarily resigned his see in 1609 , and dying shortly afterwards at Tuam , was buried in the cathedral there .
#Text=Tiomna Nuadh

#Text=Donellan was a master of the Irish language , and continued the version of the New Testament which had been commenced by John Kearney and Nicholas Walsh , bishop of Ossory , and which was completed by William O'Donnell or Daniell , who was afterwards raised to the archiepiscopal see of Tuam .

#Text=It was published in 1602 at Dublin , under the title of Tiomna Nuadh ar dtighearna agus ar slanaightheora Iosa Criosd , ar na tarruing gu firinneach as Gréigis gu gaoidheilg . Re Huilliam O Domhnuill .
#Text=It was brought out at the expense of the province of Connaught and of Sir William Usher , the clerk of the council in Ireland .
#Text=Great expectations were formed of this undertaking , and it was confidently believed that it would be the means of destroying the Roman church in Ireland .

#Text=It is a noteworthy fact that of the four scholars engaged in translating the New Testament into the Irish vernacular , three - Kearney , Walsh , and Donellan - received their education in the University of Cambridge .
#Text=Family
#Text=By his wife Elizabeth , daughter of Nicolas O'Donnell , he had issue :
#Text=- John
#Text=- James , who was knighted , and became Chief Justice of the Irish Common Pleas
#Text=- Edmund , of Killucan in the county of Westmeath
#Text=- Teigue , of Ballyheague in the county of Kildare
#Text=- Murtough , who received holy orders in the Roman Catholic Church .
